These formatioris must probably be regarded not as analogous to forms from consonant stems like faxo, faxim, &c. (aorist subjunctives or optatives) bnt as compounds of present participles with forms of the verb sum (negassim = negans sim, negassis = negans sis, &c.) So Skutsch explains the double ss. In meaning they do not differ from faxo, faxim, &c. : both are equivalent (i) to subjunctives—in prohibitions (e. g. 1097, 526), in expressions of wish, in clauses depending on caue (e. g. 523, 808), occasionally in final ne clauses, and in sentences of the type of ausim dicere; (ii) to futures or future perfects indicative—so above and in 223 (aster ni), 228 (aster si).
